      emoji: "👥",
      content: `
One of the oldest, most effective credit-building strategies is also one of the simplest: **piggybacking** on someone else's excellent credit. When you become an authorized user on their account, their entire payment history for that card gets added to your credit report.

## How Authorized User (AU) Status Works

When someone adds you as an authorized user on their credit card:

1. The **entire history** of that account appears on your credit report
2. You inherit their **payment history** (on-time or late)
3. You inherit their **credit limit** (improving your utilization)
4. You inherit their **account age** (improving your average age of accounts)
5. **You do NOT need to use the card or even possess it**

> **CRITICAL:** You are NOT responsible for the debt. The primary cardholder remains fully liable. This is purely a reporting mechanism.

## The Piggyback Effect — Real Numbers

**Scenario:** You have a thin credit file (2 cards, 2 years old, 680 score)

**Your parent/spouse has:**
- Amex Platinum: $25,000 limit, 15 years old, perfect payment history, 2% utilization
- Chase Sapphire: $15,000 limit, 10 years old, perfect payment history, 5% utilization

**After becoming AU on both:**

| Metric | Before AU | After AU | Change |
|--------|-----------|----------|--------|
| Total credit limits | $8,000 | **$48,000** | +$40,000 |
| Average age of accounts | 2 years | **~7.5 years** | +5.5 years |
| Oldest account | 2 years | **15 years** | +13 years |
| Accounts on file | 2 | **4** | +2 |
| **Estimated score** | **680** | **720-750** | **+40 to +70** |

## Who to Ask

**Best candidates (in order of preference):**

1. **Spouse/Partner** — Easiest ask; shared financial goals; you can reciprocate
2. **Parent** — Often willing to help; likely has older accounts
3. **Grandparent** — May have 20+ year old accounts; massive age benefit
4. **Sibling** — Close relationship; similar age but may have established credit
5. **Very close friend** — Only if you have deep trust (they're trusting you with their credit)

**What their card should look like:**

| Factor | Ideal | Minimum Acceptable |
|--------|-------|-------------------|
| Age | 10+ years old | 5+ years old |
| Utilization | Under 10% | Under 30% |
| Payment history | Perfect (no lates) | No lates in 2+ years |
| Limit | $10,000+ | $5,000+ |
| Status | Active and in good standing | Not maxed, not delinquent |

> **WARNING:** If the primary cardholder has ANY late payments on that account, those late payments will appear on YOUR report too. Vet their account carefully before asking.

## How to Ask (Script)

**For spouse/partner:**
> "I'm working on optimizing my credit to get the best HELOC rate. One strategy is becoming an authorized user on one of your cards — specifically the [card name] because it has great history. I wouldn't use the card; it just reports on my file. Would you be comfortable adding me?"

**For parent/family member:**
> "I'm preparing to apply for a HELOC and I'm optimizing my credit profile. One of the most effective strategies is becoming an authorized user on an older card with good payment history. Your [card name] would be perfect because of its age. I wouldn't get a card or make any charges — it purely helps my credit report. Would you be willing to add me?"

## How to Add an Authorized User

The primary cardholder can add you in three ways:

1. **Online banking** — Most issuers have an "Add Authorized User" option
2. **Mobile app** — Quick and easy; just need your name and sometimes SSN
3. **Phone** — Call the number on the back of the card

**Information typically needed:**
- Your full name (as it appears on your credit report)
- Your Social Security Number (or SIN/NI for Canada/UK)
- Your date of birth
- Your address

> **NOTE:** Some issuers (like Amex) may ask for your SSN; others (like some Chase cards) may not require it. Providing your SSN ensures the account reports to your credit file.

## Timeline for Reporting

| Issuer | Typical Reporting Time | Reports to All 3 Bureaus? |
|--------|----------------------|---------------------------|
| **American Express** | 1-2 billing cycles | Yes |
| **Chase** | 1-2 billing cycles | Yes |
| **Citi** | Next statement | Yes |
| **Discover** | 1-2 billing cycles | Yes |
| **Bank of America** | Next statement | Yes |
| **Capital One** | 1-2 billing cycles | Yes |
| **Wells Fargo** | Next statement | Yes |
| **Barclays** | Next statement | Yes |
| **US Bank** | 1-2 billing cycles | Yes |

> **Most AU accounts report within 30-60 days.** Plan accordingly for your HELOC timeline.

## What to Watch For

**Once you're an AU, monitor:**

1. **Primary cardholder's habits** — If they start carrying a balance or missing payments, remove yourself immediately
2. **The card's utilization** — Even if they pay in full, a large purchase before statement close can spike YOUR reported utilization
3. **The issuer doesn't report AU status** — A few (rare) issuers don't report AUs to credit bureaus. Verify the account appears on your report after 60 days.

## How to Remove Yourself

If things go wrong:
- Call the issuer and request removal as authorized user
- Or the primary cardholder can remove you online
- The account will eventually fall off your credit report (may take 1-2 billing cycles)
- Removing yourself won't erase the positive history that already reported

## Advanced: The Backdoor AU Strategy

**For business owners:**
- Many business cards report AU status to personal credit
- Add yourself as an AU on your own business card
- The business card's history, limit, and age report to your personal file
- Cards like the Amex Business Platinum report AUs to all three bureaus

> **INSIDER TIP:** Some people (carefully) ask to be added to a trusted friend's premium card. The key is trust — they can remove you instantly if anything goes wrong, and you never get physical access to the card. Approach this only with people you'd trust with your own credit.

## Canada & UK Notes

**Canada:** The AU strategy works similarly. Major Canadian issuers (RBC, TD, Scotia, BMO, CIBC) all report authorized users to Equifax and TransUnion. The primary cardholder must request the AU addition.

**UK:** Known as "financial associate" or "secondary cardholder." Most UK issuers (Barclaycard, HSBC, NatWest, Lloyds) report additional cardholders to Experian and Equifax. Some do NOT report to TransUnion.
      `,
