      content: `Print this checklist. Bring it to closing. Go through every item with the banker. Do not sign until every concern is addressed in writing.

---

**THE 20-POINT HELOC SIGNING CHECKLIST**

**INTEREST RATE TERMS**
- [ ] 1. Index is the WSJ Prime Rate (not proprietary)
- [ ] 2. Margin matches what was quoted (___%)
- [ ] 3. Intro rate and expiration date confirmed
- [ ] 4. Post-intro rate confirmed
- [ ] 5. Lifetime rate cap is ___% (under 18% is good)
- [ ] 6. Annual rate increase cap is ___% (4% or less)
- [ ] 7. Rate floor is ___% (lower is better; none is ideal)

**TIME PERIODS**
- [ ] 8. Draw period is ___ years (10+ required)
- [ ] 9. Draw period start and end dates are exact calendar dates
- [ ] 10. Repayment period is ___ years
- [ ] 11. No balloon payment requirement (MUST be amortized)
- [ ] 12. Recast/re-amortization is available (CRITICAL for strategy)

**FEES**
- [ ] 13. Annual fee is $___ (under $75; $0 is best)
- [ ] 14. No transaction fees per draw (MUST be $0)
- [ ] 15. No inactivity fees (MUST be $0)
- [ ] 16. Early closure fee is $___ (negotiated to $0 or under $500)
- [ ] 17. Closing costs itemized and total confirmed: $___
- [ ] 18. No hidden maintenance or service fees

**FEATURES**
- [ ] 19. Fixed-rate conversion available (Yes/No — terms confirmed)
- [ ] 20. Relationship discount applied: ___% reduction

**CRITICAL VERIFICATIONS**
- [ ] All verbal promises are reflected in the written document
- [ ] I have received a complete copy of all documents
- [ ] The 3-day rescission period is explained and documented
- [ ] I have the banker's direct phone number for post-closing questions
- [ ] I understand when my first payment is due and how much it will be

---

**HOW TO USE THIS CHECKLIST AT CLOSING**

**Step 1:** Print two copies — one for you, one for the banker.

**Step 2:** Hand the banker their copy. Say: "I review every document carefully before signing. I have a checklist of 20 key terms. I'd like to verify each one with you before we proceed."

**Step 3:** Go through each item. If the banker resists or rushes you, repeat: "I'm not delaying — I'm verifying. This protects both of us."

**Step 4:** For any discrepancy between what you were quoted and what's in the document:
- STOP signing
- Ask for an explanation in writing
- If it's an error, demand corrected documents
- If it's not an error, renegotiate or walk away

**Step 5:** Verify that ALL verbal promises are in writing. If the banker said "I'll waive the annual fee" but the document says "$75 annual fee" — the document wins. Get it changed or get a signed addendum.

> **Legal reality:** Verbal promises are unenforceable in lending. Only what's in the signed document matters. If it's not written, it doesn't exist.

**Step 6:** Confirm your 3-day rescission rights. Ask: "When does my 3-day right to cancel begin, and when does it end?" Write those dates on your calendar immediately.

---

**THE DOCUMENT REVIEW RITUAL**

The night after closing — before your 3-day window expires — do this:

1. **Re-read every page** of the disclosure with fresh eyes
2. **Verify every number** matches your checklist
3. **Check for addendums or riders** you may not have noticed
4. **Google anything you don't understand**
5. **Call the banker** with any questions (that's what the 3-day period is for)
6. **If you find a problem:** Cancel in writing before the deadline

> **The 3-day rescission is the most powerful consumer protection in lending.** A billionaire can't get out of a bad contract. But YOU can — because Regulation Z gives you 3 days to change your mind for any reason at all. Use it wisely.

---

**RED FLAGS THAT SHOULD TRIGGER IMMEDIATE CANCELLATION**

If you discover ANY of the following during your 3-day review, cancel immediately:

🚨 Rate or margin higher than quoted  
🚨 Rate floor not disclosed during application  
🚨 Balloon payment requirement discovered  
🚨 Transaction fees not previously mentioned  
🚨 Early closure fee higher than disclosed  
🚨 Index is not WSJ Prime  
🚨 Draw period shorter than quoted  
🚨 Any term that contradicts a verbal promise  

Cancelling is not rude. Cancelling is smart. The bank made a mistake — or tried to slip something past you. Either way, you don't sign bad deals. **There are always other banks.**`,
