      title: "The Risks",
      emoji: "⚠️",
      content: `
<p>Rate shopping and HELOC refinancing is powerful, but it's not free and it's not risk-free. Here's the honest assessment of what can go wrong:</p>

<h4>Risk 1: Closing Costs</h4>

<p>While HELOC closing costs are much lower than mortgage closing costs, they're not always zero.</p>

<table>
<tr><th>Fee Type</th><th>Typical Cost</th><th>When It Applies</th></tr>
<tr><td>Application fee</td><td>$0-$100</td><td>Most banks waive this</td></tr>
<tr><td>Appraisal fee</td><td>$0-$500</td><td>Some banks waive; others require full appraisal</td></tr>
<tr><td>Title search</td><td>$0-$200</td><td>Usually waived for HELOCs under $100K</td></tr>
<tr><td>Recording fee</td><td>$25-$150</td><td>County-specific, unavoidable</td></tr>
<tr><td>Annual fee</td><td>$50-$100</td><td>Ongoing, some banks waive first year</td></tr>
<tr><td>Early closure fee</td><td>$300-$500</td><td>If you close within 12-36 months</td></tr>
</table>

<p><strong>Total realistic range: $0-$500 for most borrowers.</strong> Some credit unions offer truly zero-cost HELOCs for members. Always ask: "What fees will I pay at closing, and are there any ongoing fees?"</p>

<p><strong>⚠️ Early Closure Trap:</strong> Many banks charge a $300-$500 fee if you close your HELOC within 12-36 months of opening. This is designed to prevent rate shoppers. Factor this into your cost calculation if you plan to shop again quickly.</p>

<h4>Risk 2: Credit Score Impact</h4>

<p>While the impact is usually minimal, here's what to monitor:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Hard inquiries:</strong> Each application = 1 hard inquiry. Impact: -3 to -8 points. Effect fades after 6 months.</li>
<li><strong>Multiple inquiries:</strong> Credit bureaus typically group HELOC inquiries within a 14-45 day window as a single inquiry for scoring purposes (rate shopping protection).</li>
<li><strong>Average age of accounts:</strong> Opening a new account reduces your average. If you have 10+ years of history, the impact is tiny. If you're young with limited history, it's more significant.</li>
<li><strong>Total accounts:</strong> Having too many open credit lines (6+) can be viewed negatively by some lenders, though this is a minor factor.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Mitigation:</strong> Space your HELOC applications at least 6 months apart when possible. Don't apply for any other credit (cards, loans) within 3 months of a HELOC application.</p>

<h4>Risk 3: Time Investment</h4>

<p>Each rate shopping cycle takes time:</p>

<ul>
<li>Research and comparison: 2-3 hours</li>
<li>Application (online): 30-60 minutes</li>
<li>Document gathering: 1-2 hours</li>
<li>Communication with lender: 1-2 hours over 30-60 days</li>
<li>Closing/funding: 1 hour</li>
<li><strong>Total: 6-10 hours per cycle</strong></li>
</ul>

<p>Is it worth it? If you save $1,500/year and spend 8 hours, that's <strong>$187.50 per hour</strong> of your time. Probably worth it. But know the commitment.</p>

<h4>Risk 4: Application Denial</h4>

<p>Not every application is approved. Common reasons for denial:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Credit score drop:</strong> If your score fell below the lender's threshold</li>
<li><strong>Income change:</strong> Job loss, reduced hours, or changed employment status</li>
<li><strong>Increased DTI:</strong> New debts (car loan, personal loan) pushed your debt-to-income ratio above 43-50%</li>
<li><strong>Declining home value:</strong> If your home value dropped, your CLTV may exceed the lender's maximum</li>
<li><strong>Too many recent inquiries:</strong> Some lenders flag borrowers who've applied for multiple credit lines recently</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Mitigation:</strong> Always maintain your old HELOC until the new one is confirmed open. Never count on a new HELOC until you have the confirmation in writing.</p>

<h4>When Rate Shopping ISN'T Worth It</h4>

<p>Be honest with yourself. Rate shopping may NOT make sense if:</p>

<table>
<tr><th>Scenario</th><th>Why It's Not Worth It</th></tr>
<tr><td>Small balance (&lt;$10,000)</td><td>$10,000 × 1% rate difference = $100/year. Not worth 8 hours of effort.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Short remaining timeline (&lt;12 months)</td><td>You'll pay off the HELOC before you save enough to justify the effort.</td></tr>
<tr><td>You're about to sell your home</td><td>The HELOC gets paid off at closing anyway. Save your energy for the move.</td></tr>
<tr><td>You have major credit applications coming</td><td>A HELOC inquiry could interfere with a pending mortgage or auto loan.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Your rate is already excellent</td><td>If you're at Prime + 0.00%, there's nowhere better to go.</td></tr>
<tr><td>You value simplicity over optimization</td><td>Some people genuinely prefer one bank relationship. That's valid.</td></tr>
</table>

<blockquote>The perfect is the enemy of the good. If rate shopping feels stressful or complicated, the basic HELOC acceleration strategy (from Module 5) still works incredibly well. Don't let optimization anxiety stop you from executing the fundamentals.</blockquote>
      `,
